column1: the story we know of virginia lt. governor justin fairfax is a narrative that

column4: and varying belts and ages gathered to share the mats and bond through this beautiful art. on this day
column5: i would break my silence and speak publicly to share my personal experiences with sexual assault for the very first time. i spoke of the powerlessness
column9: and blame that had trapped me in silence for over a decade. i spoke on how my first experience would set the tone for how i would allow others to treat me and how i would value myself. most importantly
column10: i spoke of how jiu-jitsu helped me to find my voice
column12: and find my place so that i could speak without fear in hopes of shining light on an issue filled with darkness. i never understood bravery until the moment i had to look out into a sea of faces
column13: which included young women who were no older than me when i was first assaulted
column14: and share a part of my life that had almost killed me; to willingly accept vulnerability and still smile and promise hope through streams of tears. i often speak of living passionately and with purpose. this was the day that i was able to embrace those words. i am so thankful to the women in this photo and the over 90 women in attendance that day for allowing me to share my story and for helping build this community. together
column15: we are powerful beyond measure. together
column16: we will never have to venture alone. .

saint agatha was born around 231 ad.  according to the history of the church
column2: she was very beautiful and had many suitors but was determined to never marry and live a contemplative spiritual life.  a high-ranking diplomat believed he could force her into marriage but she continually rejected him.  he arranged to have her arrested for her profession of christian faith during a time of intense persecution under the roman emperor decius and sat in judgment at her trial.  he sentenced her to be imprisoned in a brothel where she was repeatedly raped but bravely continued in her opposition.  she was then subjected to horrific acts of torture to the point of having her breasts cut off with pincers
column3: never wavering in her courage and resistance.  st. agatha died in prison in 251 a.d. and is revered as a great martyr of the church.  she is considered a patron saint of rape victims and breast cancer.  #stagatha #renaissancephotography  #femalesaints #patronsaint #objectification #groundfloorcontemporary #portraitphotography #saints #patronsaints #pomegranate #breastcancer #metoo #saintagathaofsicily";;en;#stagatha

column1: 40564;instagram;2019-02-10 02:34:41;FALSE;"reading for @iam_asheredee so what a great card for you
column2: i picked up on the energy of the 13th card so i'm not certain why the number 13 but i did feel something like this card represents a 13th birthday (or at least this is what i saw). the energy of this card brings to you a message of something that provides the most healing at this time in your ascension.

column1: ray 1 is the ray of power
column2: it's about not allowing any experience to influence the inner knowing (great message)

column1: el morya works closely with archangel michael and it is said that in his past incarnations he was melchoir one of the three wise men and has worked closely with earth over many many centuries and many many influential leaders.
el morya would like you to know
column2: he steps forward to give you strength and he stands beside you always
column3: to reassure you that you're moving perfectly into your power.

column1: where the card speaks of asking you to lead by example i tuned into an energy that speaks from a deep resonance of love and is reminding you of your strengths.

column1: 40744;instagram;2019-02-09 22:21:57;FALSE;"with the #metoo movement and the women‚Äôs march
column2: the conversation about gender equality + equity is only growing. @kt_mars has a passion for that conversation. read her #passionpreview: ‚Äúi am passionate about gender equity and have been for most of my life
column3: even if i didn't realize it. my passion grew over time as i began to understand my own lived experiences and how they reflected my gender identity
column4: such as when i was encouraged to run for secretary of a club rather than president or when i was told to let a male teammate lead the cheers for my swim team rather than me. while these incidents were minor
column5: there were the beginning of my awakening to the problem of gender inequality and inequity.‚Äù

column1: why gender equity? ‚Äúi am passionate about gender equity because it affects every person- men
column3: and people who are non-binary. when people face discrimination or violence due to their gender
column4: or when society tells people they are lesser due to their gender
column5: they are held back from success. how can we succeed as a society when we fail to understand and accept the intersections of identities we all carry?‚Äù

column1: to someone not interested in gender equity: ‚Äúsomeone who doesn't like my passion doesn't understand my passion and is refusing to evaluate their own role in the perpetuation of oppressive systems. it is hard to believe that each person can play a role in harmful systems
column2: but it is only when people acknowledge and actively fight against the systems that we can create change and move forward.‚Äù

column1: to someone interested in gender equity: ‚Äúi would say to start by looking at yourself and understanding your own role in gender equity. is your fight for gender equity intersectional? are you taking actions steps to combat gender inequity or are you passively watching? once you understand your own role
column2: get ready for some wonderful days and some difficult days. look at the past and honor those who have come before us. look to the future and see who will keep fighting once we are gone.‚Äù

column1: 40961;instagram;2019-02-09 18:15:17;FALSE;"does this sound like someone who was fearful? threatened? panicked? i would never have expected that she would have lied about this to this day! all the evidence and she says we attacked her. to steal her daughter. that i destroyed her daughter. no i told her daughter you need to work it out with your mom. when your primary love relationships are not rooted and safe
column2: you may not feel rooted and safe. i didn't realize then how a child dodging an authentic emotional connection with their parent sharing why she didn't want to live at her house would put me in this situation. i risked so much i risked my life. i am so disappointed in myself for not seeing the writing on the wall. when this happened a few years earlier with her son
column3: she told him i was evil. i said to him he needed to make sure he talked with his mom and not dodge her phone calls. i communicated with her openly about what happened to her kids while in our care. we tried to co-parent
column4: and she chooses to see everything as harassment. i do not think we are alone with these dysfunctional co-parenting attempts
column5: but i want people to know that violence can occur when you least expect it

column1: i often visit with teachers in my dreams and on one occasion the teacher woke me up (in my dream) and i was standing inside the mouth of a cave. i was standing facing the opening of the cave looking out into a meadow. as i was standing in the cave i began looking around at the interior
column2: the opening was about 15 feet in diameter and i'm not certain how far back the cave went because it was very dark. i did not see any writings on the walls or anything that stood out as to explain why i would be in the mouth of a cave so i turned my attentions out into the meadow.

column1: to best i can explain what the meadow looked liked is by describing it as looking like a crater covered in green shirt grass. the crater was shaped like a bowl
column2: it had a depression in the middle and the sides went up 20-30 feet high and from what i could tell is was about 200 feet round.

column1: the teacher i was with was a light being
column2: shapeless but familiar and she (don't ask how i know she was a she based on her being shapeless but i just knew). she stepped forward signifying that she wanted me to step out into the meadow. as i moved forward i was floating just above the ground and although i could or didn't see my own body i believe i was also formless (like a light cloud). the meadow was filled with sunlight and was beautiful and as i moved

column1: out from the opening of the cave i saw many formless light bodies playing and moving and communicating as if i was moving down into a park or playground and i could hear laughter and feel joy.

this place was explained to me by the teacher as heaven and it was when she told me this i saw my daughter (my wife and i lost a daughter mid way into her pregnancy) and she was a light being. she moved towards me and i felt her love and she spoke to me (when i reference speaking it's not verbal it's a wordless type of communication but so much more). this primarily is all i can remember from the dream but i wanted to share this with you.

column1: 40982;instagram;2019-02-09 17:24:09;FALSE;"""you just need to forgive and get over it"".....

so often families will tell child sex abuse survivors to forgive their abuser and ""get over it"". there is no is talk of the abuser's consequences for their criminal behavior. there is no discussion about excluding the abuser from all family interactions. there is also no discussion of protecting the child from further trauma.  the survivor is just left to believe that forgiving their abuser will suddenly make things right in their world again. well
column3: that is a lie! forgiveness is a decision that has to be made by the survivor and on a timetable that she/he sets. forced forgiveness will not bring about healing
column4: it will merely place a bandaid on a gaping wound that won't heal without proper care. there is no ""getting over"" the trauma of sexual abuse. healing is a process and it often requires professional counseling and time to peel back the layers of the emotional and mental pain that has been inflicted. the truth of the matter is
column5: these families are in a rush to suggest forgiveness because they don't want to deal with the fallout of exposing the abuser. therefore
column6: they force the survivor to quietly carry the burden of their abuse and suffer in silence. if you are a survivor of sexual abuse
column7: you need to know that you don't owe your abuser forgiveness! that is something you get to decide if you want to offer and how/when you extend it. also
column8: if you're looking at it through a spiritual lens
column9: keep in mind that forgiveness comes with a requirement for the offender to repent; meaning they have turned away from their evil ways and their actions show they have truly changed. that being said
column10: there is no justification to ask a survivor to immediately forgive because the abuser hasn't shown that they are truly repented! moreover
column11: there really should be an acknowledgment on the abuser's part for their actions and most families are asking the survivor to forgive without demanding any action on the abuser's part or without them experiencing any consequences. as we have said so many times before
column13: we acknowledge that forgiveness is your decision and no one can make that decision for you.";;en;;;;;;0;;comfortinthestorm;comfortinthestorm;;0;False;1;0;0;19;https://instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net/vp/54f950f18b6ddf9e688e2e6aca463340/5D135E37/t51.2885-15/e35/50863774_392826261470333_6062281491652918130_n.jpg?_nc_ht=instagram.fyvr3-1.fna.fbcdn.net;0;FALSE;FALSE;FALSE;english;"""you just need to forgive and get over it"".....
